WEBVTT

00:09.756 --> 00:12.506
("Dream a Little Dream of Me"
playing)

00:12.589 --> 00:14.714
♪

00:16.756 --> 00:21.798
♪ STARS SHINING BRIGHT
ABOVE YOU ♪

00:23.130 --> 00:29.381
♪ NIGHT BREEZES
SEEM TO WHISPER
I LOVE YOU ♪

00:29.464 --> 00:35.214
♪ BIRDS SINGING IN
THE SYCAMORE TREE ♪

00:35.297 --> 00:40.255
♪ DREAM A LITTLE DREAM OF ME ♪

00:42.172 --> 00:48.547
♪ SAY NIGHTY-NIGHT
AND KISS ME ♪

00:48.631 --> 00:55.047
♪ JUST HOLD ME TIGHT
AND TELL ME YOU'LL MISS ME ♪

00:55.130 --> 01:00.422
♪ WHILE I'M ALONE
AND BLUE AS CAN BE ♪

01:00.506 --> 01:06.255
♪ DREAM A LITTLE DREAM OF ME ♪

01:07.506 --> 01:14.047
♪ SWEET DREAMS
TILL SUNBEAMS FIND YOU ♪

01:14.130 --> 01:20.255
♪ SWEET DREAMS THAT LEAVE
ALL WORRIES BEHIND YOU ♪

01:20.339 --> 01:26.047
♪ BUT IN YOUR DREAMS
WHATEVER THEY BE ♪

01:26.130 --> 01:30.214
♪ DREAM A LITTLE ♪

01:30.297 --> 01:37.297
♪ DREAM OF ME ♪

01:45.839 --> 01:48.839
-Boy: WHERE IS SHE?
-Man: SHE'S IN HER STUDIO.

01:50.297 --> 01:51.964
Man:
SHE'S WORKIN'.

01:52.047 --> 01:54.172
Boy:
WHY HASN'T SHE COME BACK?

01:58.923 --> 02:01.756
(disjointed music playing)

02:01.839 --> 02:05.130
♪

02:16.506 --> 02:19.214
(music continues)

02:24.297 --> 02:26.422
(siren blaring)

02:29.923 --> 02:32.589
♪

02:39.839 --> 02:42.756
(soft classical music playing)

02:42.839 --> 02:45.339
(humming)

02:47.214 --> 02:50.381
(soft music continues
over speakers)

03:18.214 --> 03:19.422
Mm-hmm.

03:19.506 --> 03:21.464
(blender whirring)

03:21.547 --> 03:24.339
It's crap. It's cra--
Could you just
turn that down a bit?

03:24.422 --> 03:25.923
-Please. I'm trying
to concentrate...
-What?

03:26.005 --> 03:27.547
on a very delicate
operation, here.

03:27.631 --> 03:29.381
Blenders don't have
volume control.

03:29.464 --> 03:32.297
Well, that's a pathetic excuse.
Just turn it down, anyway.

03:32.381 --> 03:34.506
-(blender stops)
-Henry: Dad.

03:34.589 --> 03:37.964
-Yeah.
-I did some research
last night.

03:38.047 --> 03:40.464
-Yes?
-On golden doodles.

03:40.547 --> 03:42.756
-Oh, God--
-And they don't shed.

03:42.839 --> 03:44.381
They're hypoallergenic.

03:44.464 --> 03:46.297
-No, no-- Listen, Hen.
-They're really, really,
really cute.

03:46.381 --> 03:47.798
We're not having--
Tell him. Tell him.

03:47.881 --> 03:49.214
-It's the dog thing again.
-But why, Dad?

03:49.297 --> 03:51.631
We can't have a dog
because as I've said before,

03:51.714 --> 03:53.506
all dogs make my throat
close up,

03:53.589 --> 03:55.839
so no air gets to my lungs,
which makes me die.

03:55.923 --> 03:57.714
So it's--
It's undesirable.

03:57.798 --> 03:59.881
-But--
-Think of another pet.
You know, you can have a,

03:59.964 --> 04:01.005
a cat, or a hamster.

04:01.089 --> 04:02.923
Or-- I don't know what
kids have these days.

04:03.005 --> 04:04.756
Have a, have a vampire bat.

04:04.839 --> 04:06.255
(growls in frustration)

04:06.339 --> 04:09.172
-Is that a promise?
-Yes. That is a promise.

04:09.255 --> 04:11.589
Like the, the promise of...

04:11.673 --> 04:14.214
a road trip, too?
Just you and me?

04:14.297 --> 04:16.422
That's a low blow.
That will happen.

04:16.505 --> 04:17.630
-Henry: Will it?
-It will happen.

04:17.714 --> 04:19.339
Shit, my violin!

04:20.422 --> 04:21.923
-Jonathan: Help me, please.
-What is going on?

04:22.005 --> 04:24.047
I don't know why
I'm suddenly six years old.

04:24.130 --> 04:27.923
Oh, God. All right.
Why the tie, hmm?

04:28.005 --> 04:30.422
Not another funeral?

04:30.506 --> 04:32.297
-It's The Turd's idea.
-Oh.

04:32.381 --> 04:34.089
And no, no.

04:34.172 --> 04:37.464
-Not all my patients die.
-Oh.

04:37.547 --> 04:40.130
Why are you so dressed up?
What's his name?

04:40.214 --> 04:42.714
Ladies' tea.
Planning the fundraiser.

04:42.798 --> 04:45.631
Oh, school auction.
Did I mention I'm not going?

04:45.714 --> 04:48.297
-Oh, did I mention you are?
-I think you'll find I'm not,
my love.

04:48.381 --> 04:50.297
Isn't it enough
we give them tons
of money anyway?

04:50.381 --> 04:52.130
We actually don't
give them money.

04:52.214 --> 04:54.589
-Well, your dad does,
which is very sweet of him.
-Grace: Uh-huh.

04:54.673 --> 04:56.798
Which reminds me,
we have dinner with him
next Thursday.

04:56.881 --> 04:59.673
Right. So I have
Reardon and your dad
in the same week.

04:59.756 --> 05:02.005
I'm just the luckiest girl
in New York.

05:02.089 --> 05:04.130
-(Grace laughing)
-Don't you like Reardon?

05:04.214 --> 05:06.631
Well, do you like Reardon?
You, you like your school?

05:06.714 --> 05:07.631
-Yeah.
-Grace: Hey.

05:07.714 --> 05:09.130
And I love it.
Go on, kiss your mom.

05:09.214 --> 05:10.464
-We have to go.
-Mom--

05:10.547 --> 05:12.047
No, I'm not kissing Mom.
You do it.

05:12.130 --> 05:13.130
You need to clean this up.

05:13.214 --> 05:14.714
I'm not doing this
every single morning.

05:14.798 --> 05:16.506
No, no, I want to kiss you.
I like this.

05:16.589 --> 05:18.172
Yeah. Right.

05:18.255 --> 05:19.798
-Henry? Henry?
-Henry: What?

05:19.881 --> 05:22.964
No more smoothies.
You never, ever clean up...

05:23.047 --> 05:24.631
Jonathan: All right,
here's a question
and don't lie.

05:24.714 --> 05:27.839
Did you, in fact,
practice that thing
at all this week?

05:27.923 --> 05:29.130
Because I heard nothing.

05:29.214 --> 05:30.214
No, I practiced.

05:30.297 --> 05:31.714
-Really?
-Yeah. I swear.

05:34.005 --> 05:36.297
Do you know,
he doesn't even
think I'm any good.

05:36.381 --> 05:37.881
Mr. Rosenbaum.

05:37.964 --> 05:39.547
He actually said that, did he?

05:39.631 --> 05:41.673
No. It's not that he says it.

05:41.756 --> 05:45.798
It just-- He used to say
a lot more good stuff.

05:45.881 --> 05:48.756
I mean, sometimes
with the looks he gives me,

05:48.839 --> 05:50.255
I-I think
he wants me to quit.

05:50.339 --> 05:53.172
Well, is it possible that,
as your mom might say--

05:53.255 --> 05:55.422
(imitating Grace):
You're actually
projecting that sentiment.

05:55.506 --> 05:57.506
Because somewhere deep down,

05:57.589 --> 06:00.089
in the bowels of
your teenage psyche,

06:00.172 --> 06:01.172
you actually want to give it up.

06:01.255 --> 06:03.714
I don't want to give up.
I love violin.

06:03.798 --> 06:05.255
(in normal voice):
Okay, well,
that's great then.

06:05.339 --> 06:07.089
You know, Rosenbaum,
he's an unhappy man.

06:07.172 --> 06:08.631
It is never a good idea

06:08.714 --> 06:10.172
to take measure of ourselves

06:10.255 --> 06:11.714
through the eyes of the joyless.

06:11.798 --> 06:14.422
Well, you can be joyless.

06:16.255 --> 06:18.005
-Beg your pardon?
-Yeah.

06:18.089 --> 06:20.673
You can be joyless
when you're--
when you're stressed.

06:20.756 --> 06:22.881
Do I seem stressed a lot?

06:22.964 --> 06:25.631
Some... lately.

06:26.130 --> 06:27.214
Huh.

06:27.297 --> 06:28.589
Brilliant. Well, now--

06:28.673 --> 06:30.756
Now I'm stressed about
being stressed, so...

06:30.839 --> 06:32.881
-Thank you very much.
-You're welcome.

06:32.964 --> 06:35.631
You don't, you don't play
your violin for Rosenbaum,
anyway.

06:35.714 --> 06:37.756
You owe him your respect
and your hard work,

06:37.839 --> 06:40.381
but in the end,
your relationship with song

06:40.464 --> 06:42.506
is between you
and your music.

06:42.589 --> 06:45.089
-Got it.
-Right. And you're
brilliant, okay?

06:45.172 --> 06:46.214
So fuck Rosenbaum.

06:46.297 --> 06:48.422
-I'm telling Mom you said that.
-Take your violin,

06:48.506 --> 06:50.798
and shove it up his
Rosen-bum cheeks, okay?

06:50.881 --> 06:51.964
Dad...

06:53.130 --> 06:56.547
(lively classical music playing)

06:56.631 --> 06:59.172
♪

07:12.297 --> 07:14.339
-Jason: Morning.
-Morning.

07:15.798 --> 07:18.547
Rebecca Harkness has arrived
way too early.

07:18.631 --> 07:20.255
(whispers):
Oh. Great.

07:20.339 --> 07:22.756
Rebecca:
It just doesn't make
any sense to me.

07:22.839 --> 07:25.756
-Huh.
-One minute,
he's attentive, loving.

07:25.839 --> 07:28.547
The next minute,
he's borderline abusive.

07:28.631 --> 07:32.339
I got both swings last night.
The full pendulum.

07:32.422 --> 07:34.255
And fucking forbid

07:34.339 --> 07:37.172
I call him bipolar.
I mean...

07:37.255 --> 07:38.964
Fucking forbid!

07:39.047 --> 07:42.964
So you're back to
thinking that he's, um,
that he's bipolar.

07:43.047 --> 07:45.422
I don't know.
The mood swings...

07:46.089 --> 07:47.589
What do you think?

07:49.047 --> 07:51.339
Well, I don't know him.

07:51.422 --> 07:53.881
-I only know you.
-Meaning?

07:57.422 --> 08:00.881
-Do not give me that look.
-This is your third marriage.
Isn't it?

08:00.964 --> 08:03.089
(grunts) So, what,
we're keeping score?

08:03.172 --> 08:05.673
No. No, I'm just...

08:05.756 --> 08:08.005
-I'm not doing that.
-Okay, this is going somewhere,

08:08.089 --> 08:10.297
and I'm not exactly sure where,
other than a direction

08:10.381 --> 08:13.047
not in my favor.
So just say it.

08:14.130 --> 08:16.673
-Say it! I pay you. Say it.
-Reb--

08:17.506 --> 08:19.047
Rebecca.

08:21.005 --> 08:24.881
I have met few people
more discriminating than you.

08:24.964 --> 08:29.422
You read 100 Yelp reviews
before choosing someone
to install your carpet.

08:29.506 --> 08:32.631
Am I right?
You, you try on
20 pairs of shoes

08:32.714 --> 08:34.047
before making a choice.

08:34.130 --> 08:36.464
You do background checks
on your hair colorist.

08:36.547 --> 08:38.214
You did a background check
on me, no doubt.

08:38.297 --> 08:40.589
You vet everything.
Everything.

08:40.673 --> 08:44.047
-Which is fine. I mean,
that's appropriate.
-But...

08:44.130 --> 08:47.089
But an attractive man
comes along,

08:47.172 --> 08:50.089
and shows an interest in you,
and judgment be gone.

08:50.172 --> 08:51.798
No. That is not
what is happening.

08:51.881 --> 08:54.005
I mean, the day
that you met Kevin,

08:54.089 --> 08:55.881
you floated into this office.

08:55.964 --> 08:57.798
It was an appointment
that was made to deal

08:57.881 --> 09:00.130
with the anguish
of husband number two,

09:00.214 --> 09:03.214
only to declare that you'd met
husband number three.

09:03.297 --> 09:04.964
So, I'm saying...

09:05.881 --> 09:08.506
Maybe it's possible...

09:08.589 --> 09:12.089
that you're less of a victim
of Kevin's moods than
you are of your own.

09:12.172 --> 09:14.089
So, excuse me,
this is my fault?

09:14.172 --> 09:16.631
-No.
-It is. You're blaming me.

09:16.714 --> 09:19.381
I'm not blaming you.
I'm just saying
there's a particular

09:19.464 --> 09:21.130
type of person that
you want to be with,

09:21.214 --> 09:22.714
and maybe you're
a little too quick

09:22.798 --> 09:25.047
to see that person
in the men that you meet,

09:25.130 --> 09:27.464
instead of seeing
what's actually there.

09:28.631 --> 09:30.839
(horn honks)

09:30.923 --> 09:33.673
Grace (over phone):
UGH. WELL, I'LL PROBABLY
NEVER SEE HER AGAIN

09:33.756 --> 09:36.422
BECAUSE THEY HIRE YOU
TO GIVE THEM THE HARD TRUTHS,

09:36.506 --> 09:38.923
AND THEN, THEN THEY FIRE YOU
FOR DELIVERING THEM.

09:39.005 --> 09:40.589
Well, just--
just up your prices.

09:40.673 --> 09:43.673
The more exclusive you seem,
the more she'll come begging.

09:43.756 --> 09:46.964
Wow. (chuckles)
I have some bad news.

09:47.047 --> 09:48.464
The, um,

09:48.547 --> 09:52.381
the dress code
for the fundraiser
is fancy-glam.

09:52.464 --> 09:53.673
I'm not wearing a tux.

09:53.756 --> 09:55.714
Grace:
LISTEN, THIS IS FOR
HENRY'S SCHOOL.

09:55.798 --> 09:58.047
If I can tough out
a ladies' tea,

09:58.130 --> 10:01.089
you can stomach one fundraiser.
For Henry.

10:01.172 --> 10:03.756
I will do it.
But not for Henry's school.

10:03.839 --> 10:05.506
I will do it for you.

10:05.589 --> 10:06.881
Because you're hot.

10:06.964 --> 10:09.839
Anyway, I'm here.
Okay?

10:09.923 --> 10:11.881
Later, smart ass.

10:11.964 --> 10:13.381
Yeah, later. Bye.

10:14.631 --> 10:16.047
(doorbell chimes)

10:19.214 --> 10:20.673
-Come in.
-Hi.

10:21.839 --> 10:24.547
-Let me take your coat.
-Yes.

10:25.923 --> 10:27.714
They're waiting for you
upstairs.

10:27.798 --> 10:29.673
(laughter)

10:30.589 --> 10:32.464
-Sally: Hello!
-Sorry I'm late.

10:32.547 --> 10:34.714
-Not a problem.
-(distant baby babbling)

10:34.798 --> 10:36.631
-We have a new mom.
-Oh.

10:36.714 --> 10:38.214
A Scholarship.

10:38.297 --> 10:40.547
She brought her infant.
She's changing her
in the bathroom.

10:40.631 --> 10:42.089
You look fabulous.

10:42.172 --> 10:43.547
-Oh, hi, Grace.
-Grace: Hi.

10:43.631 --> 10:45.255
-Hi.
-Grace: Is she, uh,
on the committee?

10:45.339 --> 10:47.506
Uh, wants to be
an involved parent.

10:47.589 --> 10:49.381
Hi. Hi, hi. Sorry.

10:49.798 --> 10:51.297
-Hey.
-Thanks.

10:51.381 --> 10:53.506
Sylvia:
Did any of you even know
that she was coming?

10:53.589 --> 10:55.798
I mean, I'm usually
the first one to
learn of anything.

10:55.881 --> 10:57.297
People can't wait
to tell me stuff.

10:57.381 --> 10:59.631
Amanda:
Because you're so quick
to disapprove.

10:59.714 --> 11:01.798
Well, exactly.

11:01.881 --> 11:03.631
Diane:
All right, we should
get going here.

11:03.714 --> 11:04.839
Woman:
Sorry!

11:04.923 --> 11:06.130
Sylvia:
She's a bit nervous.

11:06.214 --> 11:08.130
She's back to being
the auctioneer.

11:08.214 --> 11:10.089
Jolene:
I thought you got
the guy from Sotheby's.

11:10.172 --> 11:12.381
Diane:
No, he dropped out.
We'll be fine.

11:12.464 --> 11:13.756
-I've done this before.
-Hi.

11:13.839 --> 11:15.255
Hi. Hi.

11:15.339 --> 11:17.172
I'm Grace Fraser.

11:17.255 --> 11:19.381
Elena Alves.
Nice to meet you.

11:19.464 --> 11:21.339
-Hi.
-Elena has a boy
in fourth grade?

11:21.422 --> 11:23.130
You said his name was Miguel?

11:23.214 --> 11:25.756
-Yeah, yeah.
-Your baby's gorgeous.

11:25.839 --> 11:27.547
-Thank you.
-Hello. Boy or girl?

11:27.631 --> 11:29.005
Girl. Teresa.

11:29.089 --> 11:30.631
Oh. Teresa.

11:30.714 --> 11:32.881
-I love your eyelashes.
-Okay, come on, folks.

11:32.964 --> 11:34.130
The auction's tomorrow.

11:34.214 --> 11:35.923
Thank you so much
for letting me join.

11:36.005 --> 11:39.089
Are you kidding?
We're happy to get
all the help we can.

11:39.172 --> 11:41.798
That you even have the time
with two kids.

11:41.881 --> 11:43.923
I have twins. So regret it.

11:44.005 --> 11:46.464
-Jolene!
-(all chuckling)

11:46.547 --> 11:48.798
I mean, they're
so much work, right?

11:48.881 --> 11:50.673
Sylvia:
Okay, let's, uh...

11:50.756 --> 11:51.964
let's rank the items.

11:52.047 --> 11:53.839
-Yes.
-We'll start with
the least expensive.

11:53.923 --> 11:57.214
Work our way up to the...
the big tickets.

11:57.297 --> 11:58.798
Amanda:
There's a lot of stuff here.

11:58.881 --> 12:02.130
Well, we have over 200
people confirmed coming.
That's a record.

12:02.214 --> 12:04.798
Thanks to the Spensers
lending us their home.

12:04.881 --> 12:06.714
I did a walk-through yesterday.
Oh, my God.

12:06.798 --> 12:08.089
Mm. Did you see
the David Hockneys?

12:08.172 --> 12:10.214
Two of them,
on facing walls
in the dining room.

12:10.297 --> 12:12.756
-And what about Suki's closet?
-Oh, I'll get there.

12:12.839 --> 12:14.339
Maybe Monday night,
with any luck.

12:14.422 --> 12:15.798
-Yes!
-(all chattering)

12:15.881 --> 12:17.214
Diane:
Okay, let's do this. Okay!

12:17.297 --> 12:21.130
(clears throat)
We got four separate stays
in the Hamptons.

12:21.214 --> 12:23.214
A pair in Vail and Aspen.

12:23.297 --> 12:25.589
A cooking lesson at Tribeca
for eight.

12:25.673 --> 12:27.214
You never know how much
those go for.

12:27.297 --> 12:28.547
Amanda:
Stem-cell facelift.

12:28.631 --> 12:29.839
Does anybody really
believe in those?

12:29.923 --> 12:32.547
Jolene:
Kathy Sennot got one.
Did not work.

12:32.631 --> 12:34.130
Sally:
We have a bunch of consults.

12:34.214 --> 12:36.714
A college admissions counselor.
A pre-school admissions
counselor.

12:36.798 --> 12:38.506
A genealogist that'll
come to your house.

12:38.589 --> 12:39.964
-That could actually go.
-(baby crying)

12:40.047 --> 12:41.881
Jolene:
I don't see any artists.
Where are the artists?

12:41.964 --> 12:43.589
Sylvia:
Are you saying
we can't scratch up

12:43.673 --> 12:45.839
one lousy playwright
in all of New York City?

12:45.923 --> 12:48.422
Grace, maybe you could donate
a therapy session.

12:48.506 --> 12:50.756
I am not doing that.
That is not happening.

12:50.839 --> 12:53.339
Why not? "Do I hear $500
on saving your marriage?"

12:53.422 --> 12:55.798
Uh, 500, and I will
throw in my husband.

12:55.881 --> 12:57.506
Sally:
Grace, you know
what would be awesome?

12:57.589 --> 12:59.464
I think Jonathan
would be a huge get.

12:59.547 --> 13:01.130
You want to auction Jonathan?

13:01.214 --> 13:03.756
-Sally: Well...
-Yes! I'm putting him up.

13:03.839 --> 13:05.798
Uh, Grace's husband is a doctor.

13:05.881 --> 13:07.756
-He was featured in
"New York" magazine.
-Oh.

13:07.839 --> 13:11.756
Sylvia:
He's an oncologist, Sally.
Who's gonna bid on cancer?

13:11.839 --> 13:14.923
Amanda:
A private, after-hours tour
at the Guggenheim.

13:15.005 --> 13:17.714
They're doing the Salon
de la Rose Croix.

13:17.798 --> 13:21.130
You know, I was just there
on Tuesday for the Chagall
exhibit.

13:21.214 --> 13:23.756
I swear, I actually
felt light-headed.

13:23.839 --> 13:25.798
Sally:
I don't really get Chagall.

13:25.881 --> 13:28.089
Amanda (laughing):
I mean, who doesn't get Chagall?

13:28.172 --> 13:30.798
Jolene:
Me. One minute he's a modernist.

13:30.881 --> 13:34.214
Then it's stained glass.
The guy's all over the place.

13:34.297 --> 13:37.339
If he were alive today,
they'd put him on Prozac...

13:37.422 --> 13:41.547
♪

13:53.089 --> 13:56.047
(phone vibrating)

13:57.714 --> 13:59.839
-Hey. Hold on.
-(phone clicks)

14:01.047 --> 14:04.172
Tell me that wasn't odd.
My God!

14:04.255 --> 14:06.130
She was just feeding her child.

14:06.214 --> 14:08.172
Sylvia (whispering):
Oh, no. No, no, no, no, no.

14:08.255 --> 14:09.964
There was definitely
something more going on.

14:10.047 --> 14:12.172
-Excuse me.
-Grace (over phone):
LIKE WHAT?

14:12.255 --> 14:13.673
Like she was...

14:13.756 --> 14:16.005
Point!
Point your foot!

14:16.089 --> 14:19.547
Like she was being
passive-aggressive about it.
You didn't get that?

14:19.631 --> 14:21.255
No.

14:21.339 --> 14:24.339
You know, I've seen her
at the school before.

14:24.422 --> 14:27.381
SITTING ACROSS THE STREET
ON ONE OF THOSE BENCHES.

14:32.130 --> 14:35.714
AFTER SHE DROPS HER SON OFF,
SHE JUST SITS THERE.

14:36.339 --> 14:38.005
Grace:
WITH THE BABY?

14:38.089 --> 14:40.172
Sylvia:
WELL NOW WITH THE BABY.
BEFORE WHEN SHE WAS PREGNANT.

14:40.255 --> 14:42.214
She wouldn't even be
reading a book.

14:42.297 --> 14:44.214
I feel like telling her,
"You live in New York.

14:44.297 --> 14:46.881
It is a crime not to be
frantically busy."
Who just...

14:46.964 --> 14:49.589
SITS AROUND QUIETLY?

14:49.673 --> 14:51.714
What an unfathomable
state of being.

14:51.798 --> 14:54.047
Albeit with...
(laughs)

14:54.130 --> 14:57.214
spectacular breasts.

14:57.297 --> 15:00.422
-You're bad.
-OH, MY GOD.
THEY WERE BEAUTIFUL.

15:00.506 --> 15:01.881
(whispers):
Up, up, up, up, up.

15:01.964 --> 15:03.381
Up, up, tall.
Get your-- Tall.

15:03.464 --> 15:05.214
-Shoulders down.
Shoulders down.
-(giggles)

15:05.297 --> 15:07.714
Stop smiling.
Stop smiling!

15:07.798 --> 15:10.089
(horns honking)

15:14.339 --> 15:16.631
(siren blaring)

15:31.047 --> 15:32.589
(kissing noises)

15:32.673 --> 15:34.631
Elena, what's wrong?

15:41.381 --> 15:44.839
Grace:
IT WAS HOSTILE.
IT JUST WAS.

15:44.923 --> 15:47.214
But I don't blame her.
I mean, we were
talking about art.

15:47.297 --> 15:50.881
We were talking about money.
It was, it was pretty vulgar.

15:50.964 --> 15:53.172
And she was just
trying to say,
"Hey, here I am.

15:53.255 --> 15:55.589
"I'm a real, real woman.
I'm a real mom.

15:55.673 --> 15:57.506
I'm struggling, and--"
(clicks tongue)

15:57.589 --> 16:00.798
I don't know. Sometimes I think
we should move out of the city.

16:02.964 --> 16:06.214
Said the most New York person
I've ever met in my life.

16:07.089 --> 16:08.798
No, but don't you
worry sometimes

16:08.881 --> 16:10.839
that you're raising your son
in a bubble?

16:10.923 --> 16:13.964
I thought that was the whole
essence of modern parenting,
isn't it?

16:14.047 --> 16:16.673
Keep them protected from reality
for as long as possible

16:16.756 --> 16:17.964
so that when they
finally emerge,

16:18.047 --> 16:19.714
they can't cope
and end up self-harming.

16:19.798 --> 16:22.506
-I thought we were doing
really well at that.
-Mm.

16:22.589 --> 16:25.839
Wow. What about
Schenectady, huh?

16:25.923 --> 16:29.756
-I've heard nice things
about Schenectady.
-It sounds horrible.

16:29.839 --> 16:32.089
Even phonetically.

16:32.172 --> 16:34.422
So, is this
a serious conversation?

16:34.506 --> 16:36.047
Yeah.

16:36.130 --> 16:39.005
Yep. Manhattan is
a lonely place.

16:39.089 --> 16:40.464
I mean,
when you think about it,

16:40.547 --> 16:42.798
we don't have a lot
of close friends.

16:42.881 --> 16:45.631
Well, that's only 'cause
we hate everyone.

16:45.714 --> 16:48.798
You hate everyone.
I don't.

16:48.881 --> 16:51.172
I wouldn't call us isolated.

16:51.255 --> 16:53.547
Our days are stuffed
with people and their problems.

16:53.631 --> 16:56.964
I mean, we're right up close
with them at their most
vulnerable.

16:57.047 --> 16:58.547
It's not a conventional
social life,

16:58.631 --> 17:00.673
but in terms of meaningful
human interaction,

17:00.756 --> 17:02.422
I would say we did
very well.

17:03.464 --> 17:06.339
-Mm.
-I don't like you being lonely.

17:06.422 --> 17:07.798
Grace:
Mm.

17:09.130 --> 17:11.589
You lonely in there?

17:11.673 --> 17:13.589
Would you like some company?

17:15.172 --> 17:17.005
Would you like to be washed?

17:17.089 --> 17:20.172
Grace, Dr. Fraser,
with his magic hands.

17:20.255 --> 17:21.464
(Grace laughs)

17:21.547 --> 17:23.005
Shall I get my rubber gloves?

17:23.089 --> 17:26.005
-Come on. Come in.
-I'm coming, Grace.

17:26.089 --> 17:28.839
(lively orchestral music
playing)

17:28.964 --> 17:31.089
♪

17:44.005 --> 17:46.172
(pop song playing
over speakers)

17:54.756 --> 17:56.964
(song changes over speakers)

18:02.005 --> 18:03.798
(water running)

18:03.881 --> 18:05.964
(indistinct chatter)

18:16.297 --> 18:17.464
Grace?

18:17.547 --> 18:18.964
Hi.

18:20.297 --> 18:21.673
Elena.

18:21.756 --> 18:24.923
-We met at the
fundraiser committee.
-Yes, yes. Of course.

18:25.005 --> 18:26.422
How are you?

18:26.506 --> 18:29.923
-I'm, I'm well. (laughs)
-Good.

18:30.005 --> 18:33.964
Thank you so much for
making me feel so welcome.

18:35.422 --> 18:37.339
The other women...

18:37.422 --> 18:40.172
I don't know,
I felt like an intruder.

18:40.255 --> 18:43.172
But you made me feel
at home. So...

18:44.172 --> 18:46.089
-Thank you.
-(laughing)

18:46.172 --> 18:48.923
Well, I know that, um...

18:49.005 --> 18:51.089
Everybody was very happy
to have you there.

18:51.172 --> 18:54.089
We need all the help
we can get. (laughs)

18:58.589 --> 19:00.047
How can I help?

19:01.673 --> 19:04.631
-'Cause nobody actually
made me do anything.
-(laughs)

19:04.714 --> 19:08.172
Um, I suppose...

19:08.255 --> 19:12.172
because most of the work
was already done, and...

19:12.255 --> 19:15.047
And you were occupied
with your sweet baby.

19:15.130 --> 19:16.673
Yeah.

19:16.756 --> 19:19.047
But I want to be a part of it.

19:20.214 --> 19:21.547
At school.

19:23.005 --> 19:24.381
I really do.

19:25.881 --> 19:27.047
I know.

19:29.339 --> 19:31.047
I really do.

19:39.798 --> 19:41.255
(coughs)

19:45.214 --> 19:47.964
Grace: (sighs)
She was just standing there.

19:48.047 --> 19:49.589
Naked.

19:50.297 --> 19:51.798
-(sighs)
-Yeah?

19:51.881 --> 19:55.547
I'm all for women
being comfortable
with their bodies,

19:55.631 --> 19:58.089
but it was...

19:58.172 --> 20:00.255
-Weird.
-Good weird?

20:00.923 --> 20:03.089
Were you a little bit...

20:03.172 --> 20:04.547
-St--
-Aroused?

20:04.631 --> 20:07.339
-No.
-Jonathan: Oh, Christ.
We're nearly there.

20:07.422 --> 20:08.839
The sooner we can get out,
the better.

20:08.923 --> 20:11.297
Look, I've got that
early flight to Cleveland.

20:11.381 --> 20:13.130
When do you get back?

20:13.214 --> 20:15.631
Possibly tomorrow night,
if I can get away,

20:15.714 --> 20:18.506
but you know,
I do hate to forfeit
my Hyatt reward points.

20:18.589 --> 20:20.839
And that's how you get
the complimentary breakfast,
Grace.

20:21.547 --> 20:23.005
Okay, here we are.

20:23.089 --> 20:25.547
Slump, dread, sob...

20:25.631 --> 20:27.714
-Despair--
-Look at me.

20:27.798 --> 20:29.255
Mm.

20:30.464 --> 20:32.631
I'm very proud of my wife.
Come on.

20:38.130 --> 20:40.547
(clicking elevator button)

20:40.631 --> 20:42.673
-(Grace clears throat)
-Oh, Christ. They're coming.

20:42.756 --> 20:44.130
-(commotion)
-Hold the elevator!

20:44.214 --> 20:46.255
Oh. Sorry. Sorry!
Just--

20:46.339 --> 20:48.047
(doors shut, elevator whirs)

20:48.130 --> 20:50.964
-Couldn't face it.
-You're so bad.

20:51.047 --> 20:54.964
-(sighs)
-Profound, and
existential dread.

20:58.172 --> 21:00.005
(indistinct chatter)

21:00.089 --> 21:02.255
♪ DO DO DO DO ♪

21:02.339 --> 21:05.047
-Woman:
Hi. May I take your coat?
-Grace: Thank you.

21:05.130 --> 21:06.255
Woman:
Thank you.

21:06.339 --> 21:10.089
♪ DO DO DO DO,
DO DO DO ♪

21:10.172 --> 21:12.005
-Woman: Thanks.
-Jonathan: Thank you.

21:14.214 --> 21:17.172
♪ COUNT EVERY STAR ♪

21:17.255 --> 21:19.130
♪ IN THE MIDNIGHT SKY ♪

21:19.214 --> 21:21.089
-Man: Champagne?
-Thank you.

21:21.172 --> 21:23.506
Thank God. Thank you.
I love you very much.

21:23.589 --> 21:24.923
(chuckles)

21:25.005 --> 21:26.631
I thought there was
gonna be some glam.

21:26.714 --> 21:28.881
-I didn't think this much.
-Ugh.

21:29.798 --> 21:31.089
Can we hide?

21:31.172 --> 21:33.798
Let's go and pretend to be
interested in those Hockneys,
mm?

21:33.881 --> 21:35.673
No, we're stuck here for a bit.

21:35.756 --> 21:38.506
We have to have cocktails
with the headmaster first.

21:38.589 --> 21:39.964
-Come on.
-Jonathan: Oh, Christ.

21:40.047 --> 21:42.047
-Robert. Hi.
-Robert: Grace.

21:42.130 --> 21:43.506
-Jonathan.
-Hey.

21:43.589 --> 21:45.089
Oh, thank you both
so much for coming.

21:45.172 --> 21:46.422
-There you are.
-It's a--

21:46.506 --> 21:48.089
-(laughs) Dad?
-Hello.

21:48.172 --> 21:49.255
Robert:
Franklin.

21:49.339 --> 21:51.297
Such an honor and
a privilege, sir.

21:51.381 --> 21:54.214
-You left out "thrill."
-Robert (laughing):
Yes, I did.

21:54.297 --> 21:55.756
(Grace laughs)

21:55.839 --> 21:57.422
Well, thank you for coming.

21:57.506 --> 21:59.005
I'm not coming.
I'm going.

21:59.089 --> 22:02.005
-Grace: Really? Now?
-I bid on the
silent auction.

22:02.089 --> 22:06.047
I'm apt to win one of
Henry Ford's
original dipsticks.

22:06.130 --> 22:09.798
-Grace: Mm.
-I would like to be long gone
before that happens.

22:09.881 --> 22:11.547
-Jonathan.
-Franklin.

22:11.631 --> 22:12.756
You're looking well.

22:12.839 --> 22:14.047
I am?

22:14.130 --> 22:15.673
Uh, very surprising.
Thank you.

22:15.756 --> 22:18.506
-Dinner Thursday?
-Absolutely.

22:18.589 --> 22:19.714
-Hello.
-Hi.

22:19.798 --> 22:22.089
-Hi. Hi, hi.
-Franklin: Hi, darling.

22:22.923 --> 22:24.506
-Jonathan.
-Franklin.

22:24.589 --> 22:26.381
You're not gonna
fucking believe this.

22:26.464 --> 22:28.172
-Grace: What?
-They're not even here.

22:28.255 --> 22:30.005
-Grace: Who?
-The Spensers.

22:30.089 --> 22:31.172
Oh.

22:31.255 --> 22:32.756
What, you don't think
that's rude?

22:32.839 --> 22:34.881
We could take it as rude
or it could be,

22:34.964 --> 22:37.047
"While we're gonna be
out of town,

22:37.130 --> 22:39.506
happy to let you
use our palace."

22:39.589 --> 22:41.506
Can't you ever
just be not nice?

22:41.589 --> 22:43.339
-Oh, she can, I promise you.
-(laughing)

22:43.422 --> 22:44.964
You hear those fucks
didn't show?

22:45.047 --> 22:47.673
It's a fabulous turnout.
I was worried that people
wouldn't show,

22:47.756 --> 22:49.839
and it seems that
absolutely everybody
is here,

22:49.923 --> 22:51.547
so we can relax.

22:52.589 --> 22:53.839
There she is.

22:53.923 --> 22:55.923
Jolene:
Ugh. Our lactator-in-chief.

22:56.005 --> 22:58.005
Grace:
She looks a bit uncomfortable.

22:58.089 --> 23:00.214
That's the mom
I was telling you about.

23:00.297 --> 23:02.172
-Oh, that's her?
-Mm-hmm.

23:02.255 --> 23:04.047
-The nudist?
-I want those boobs.

23:04.130 --> 23:05.756
Amanda:
You know, we should
go talk to her.

23:05.839 --> 23:07.798
She must be feeling
so awkward.

23:07.881 --> 23:10.381
Sally:
Actually, she seems okay.

23:10.464 --> 23:13.130
Mm, maybe better than okay.

23:13.214 --> 23:15.839
-Jonathan:
Am I missing something?
-Amanda: Look at the men.

23:15.923 --> 23:17.381
Sally:
Like Pavlov's dogs.

23:17.464 --> 23:20.673
Grace, I, I think
she might be
looking at you.

23:20.756 --> 23:22.798
Really? Is she?

23:23.631 --> 23:25.964
Jonathan:
Uh, yeah. I think she is.

23:26.047 --> 23:27.422
Sylvia:
Well, here you all are.

23:27.506 --> 23:29.464
I think they'd like
to get started.
It's bidding time.

23:29.547 --> 23:31.923
-Start herding the people.
-Diane: All right. Here we go.

23:32.005 --> 23:33.381
Come on.

23:33.464 --> 23:35.547
Is that enough?
We've put in
an appearance.

23:35.631 --> 23:37.172
-Can we go?
-Would you stop?

23:37.255 --> 23:40.130
Hey. I'll make it
up to you later.

23:40.214 --> 23:43.756
Make it up to me now.
Let's find a room.
They must have a few.

23:43.839 --> 23:46.714
-You're so bad.
-Come on.
In Suki's closet.

23:46.798 --> 23:49.339
-In Suki's clothes.
Both of us.
-Stop!

23:49.422 --> 23:50.964
Make an Englishman happy.
Come on.

23:51.047 --> 23:52.923
(Grace laughs)

23:53.005 --> 23:55.130
-Aah.
-(glass clicks on table)

23:55.214 --> 23:56.839
-You know what
I love about this?
-What?

23:56.923 --> 23:58.172
You could never tell
they were rich.

23:58.255 --> 24:00.673
It's all so classy
and understated.

24:01.631 --> 24:03.172
Sally:
Hi. We're ready to start.

24:03.255 --> 24:04.589
Welcome, welcome,
welcome.

24:04.673 --> 24:07.547
I'm Sally Maybury,
head of the auction
committee,

24:07.631 --> 24:11.589
-for our wonderful
Reardon School!
-(all applauding)

24:11.673 --> 24:13.089
-Woo!
-(cheering)

24:13.172 --> 24:15.547
Sally:
We have a positively fabulous

24:15.631 --> 24:17.130
afternoon in store for you.

24:17.214 --> 24:19.923
Now, some of you
might be thinking,

24:20.005 --> 24:22.547
"Don't I already pay enough
in tuition?"

24:22.631 --> 24:24.506
-Woman: Damn right!
-(laughter)

24:24.589 --> 24:28.381
Yes. Of course you do.
Yes, I feel the same way.

24:28.464 --> 24:30.631
But, it is our responsibility

24:30.714 --> 24:32.798
to make sure that
Reardon can accept

24:32.881 --> 24:34.631
the students it wants to accept,

24:34.714 --> 24:37.089
and that those students
are able to attend,

24:37.172 --> 24:38.964
despite their financial
circumstances,

24:39.047 --> 24:43.130
ensuring that the name Reardon
is always synonymous with...

24:43.214 --> 24:46.172
-Diversity!
-(applauding)

24:47.881 --> 24:49.547
Sally:
And of course,
we have to make sure that

24:49.631 --> 24:51.089
our teachers are so well paid

24:51.172 --> 24:53.255
that we do not lose them
to other schools.

24:53.339 --> 24:55.964
-We love our teachers
at Reardon! Woo!
-(applauding)

24:56.047 --> 24:58.297
Just not enough to
invite them to the party.

24:58.381 --> 25:00.005
-Shush.
-Sally: Okay, now,

25:00.089 --> 25:03.381
Diane Porter is gonna
start the party. Let's go!

25:03.464 --> 25:05.798
-Woo!
-(all applauding)

25:05.881 --> 25:09.255
Diane:
Before we turn to
our scheduled items for bid...

25:10.506 --> 25:11.881
Observe.

25:11.964 --> 25:15.339
This may look like
an ordinary glass
of tap water,

25:15.422 --> 25:17.214
but it is much
more than that.

25:17.297 --> 25:20.923
This is very special water

25:21.005 --> 25:24.089
that will serve to
prime the pipes

25:24.172 --> 25:26.589
to your generously
deep pockets.

25:26.673 --> 25:28.214
-All: Aw...
-(laughter)

25:28.297 --> 25:30.422
Diane:
What is the value,
you may ask,

25:30.506 --> 25:32.422
of an ordinary glass
of tap water?

25:32.506 --> 25:33.673
That depends.

25:33.756 --> 25:37.798
What is the value of
your children's education?

25:37.881 --> 25:40.172
The value of his
or her teachers?

25:40.255 --> 25:42.923
The opportunity
of the less fortunate

25:43.005 --> 25:46.506
to enjoy the privilege
of your offspring.

25:46.589 --> 25:51.714
Who will bid $1,000

25:51.798 --> 25:54.214
for this glass of water?

25:54.297 --> 25:57.547
Who is gonna stand up
and clang that bell?

25:57.631 --> 26:00.464
-Woman: 1,000!
-Diane: $1,000!

26:00.547 --> 26:03.881
-Thank you. Money for our kids.
-(applauding)

26:03.964 --> 26:06.047
-Man: 2,000!
-Diane: 2,000!

26:06.130 --> 26:08.673
3,000...

26:08.756 --> 26:10.422
5,000 right here...

26:10.506 --> 26:12.714
-Man: Eight!
-Diane: 8,000, right here!

26:12.798 --> 26:15.756
-Man: I bid 10!
-Diane: 10,000!

26:15.839 --> 26:18.464
(applauding)

26:22.130 --> 26:25.089
-(toilet flushing)
-Grace: Oh, uh...

26:25.172 --> 26:26.506
Elena. Sorry--

26:26.589 --> 26:29.631
-I...
-(whispers): Sorry.

26:29.714 --> 26:32.464
-(exhales)
-Grace: Are you okay?

26:35.673 --> 26:37.673
(exhales)

26:38.172 --> 26:39.506
(sighs)

26:42.464 --> 26:43.839
(blows nose)

26:44.422 --> 26:46.005
(groans)

26:48.506 --> 26:50.464
I'm sorry.

26:50.547 --> 26:51.923
(sniffles)

26:52.005 --> 26:55.506
(exhales)
'Cause sometimes
I just feel...

26:55.589 --> 26:57.172
overwhelmed.

26:59.714 --> 27:01.339
And lost.

27:02.172 --> 27:04.005
-Grace: Mm.
-I...

27:07.047 --> 27:09.005
Do you ever feel that?

27:10.297 --> 27:12.506
If you ever want to talk...

27:14.047 --> 27:16.214
For free, uh...

27:18.005 --> 27:20.798
I apologize.
I didn't mean it
to sound like that.

27:20.881 --> 27:23.589
But if you do ever
wanna talk...

27:26.339 --> 27:28.714
You're so kind.
Thank you.

27:29.589 --> 27:31.589
And please,
don't be intimidated.

27:31.673 --> 27:34.589
The parents at Reardon
can be a little, um...

27:35.631 --> 27:37.547
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

27:38.047 --> 27:39.381
But...

27:40.381 --> 27:43.130
Most of them are very kind.
They're...

27:43.214 --> 27:46.673
They are nice people.
Kind people and...

27:46.756 --> 27:49.089
But you are the most kind.

27:50.547 --> 27:52.005
It's true.

27:53.214 --> 27:54.881
I feel it.

28:03.756 --> 28:05.422
Diane:
All right, our next item...

28:05.506 --> 28:07.506
-Knicks tickets. Wow.
-(excited chatter)

28:07.589 --> 28:09.964
You can rub elbows
with Spike Lee.

28:10.047 --> 28:11.881
Pitch him your idea
for a new movie.

28:11.964 --> 28:14.506
Hey, you never know.
They might even win the game.

28:14.589 --> 28:15.881
(all exclaiming)

28:15.964 --> 28:18.172
All right. Who's gonna
take these tickets
off my hands?

28:18.255 --> 28:20.798
Let's start the bidding
at 1,500.

28:20.881 --> 28:22.964
-Thank you.
-Diane: 1,500, right here.

28:23.047 --> 28:26.255
2,000, in the front. 2,500.
Do I hear 3,000?

28:26.339 --> 28:28.506
-Diane: 3,000 over here. 35?
-Man: Yeah.

28:28.589 --> 28:30.839
-Diane: 4,000, near the piano.
-Man: Right here.

28:30.923 --> 28:32.964
Diane:
$6,000!

28:33.047 --> 28:35.798
-Going once, going twice...
-Elena?

28:35.881 --> 28:38.547
-Diane: Yours, for--
-Oh, hi.

28:38.631 --> 28:41.381
I'm going home
'cause I forgot to pump,

28:41.464 --> 28:43.172
and it's getting a bit
uncomfortable.

28:43.255 --> 28:45.172
Oh. I have a car.

28:45.255 --> 28:47.381
